&quot;And yet the forms post&quot;


________________________________
From: rest-disc=
uss@yahoogroups.com [rest-discuss@yahoogroups.com] on behalf of Mike Kelly =
[mikekelly321@...]
Sent: 04 January 2012 13:29
To: Jan Algermissen
Cc=
: REST Discuss; iansrobinson@...
Subject: Re: [rest-discuss] Reasons =
to use forms





On Wed, Jan 4, 2012 at 12:54 PM, Jan Algermissen &lt;jan.alg=
ermissen@...&lt;mailto:jan.algermissen@...&gt;&gt; wrote:


On Jan 4, =
2012, at 1:18 PM, Mike Kelly wrote:

&gt; I wasn&#39;t saying there
&gt; is anything =
actually &#39;wrong&#39; with forms, just that introducing them to
&gt; a machine app =
is (for the time being) a costly and mostly fruitless
&gt; effort - it increas=
es the complexity of consuming the application (by
&gt; adding a requirement t=
o understand form processing rules) without
&gt; delivering much by way of imp=
roving evolvability - it doesn&#39;t bring
&gt; much to the table, and many client=
s will either get it wrong or hack
&gt; around it anyway. This may well improv=
e in the future but right now it
&gt; doesn&#39;t seem like a good option from the=
 practical, cost-benefit point
&gt; of view (not the architecturally pure one)=
.

A benefit of forms is that they can provide data to include in the corre=
sponding submission that needs not or must not (due to volatility) be remem=
bered by the client.

An example would be the current price of an item. Ins=
tead of constructing an order and including a remembered price, the current=
 price can be right in the form for the client to review and then put into =
the submission request.


This is possible without forms by making the carr=
ied values a part of the necessary representations and making the client be=
haviour (carrying the value) part of the &#39;domain application protocol&#39;. The=
 difference with forms is that the information that the client can potentia=
lly carry is arbitrary with forms as far as the client is concerned, and th=
e control of the resultant request is completely in the hands of the server=
 presenting the initial form.

There is a pretty serious security implicati=
on of this approach, in that the integrity of the client&#39;s request is lost =
to the server which in many cases will belong to an external organisation. =
I imagine this would raise security concerns about how far (if at all) such=
 a mechanism should be allowed to go; e.g. requiring a same-domain policy o=
r removing the ability for additional, arbitrary inputs to be injected into=
 the resulting request. These sorts of measures would make a big dent in th=
e benefits of taking the form approach. If half of your clients were ok wit=
h that, and the other half weren&#39;t - could you really make significant chan=
ges to those forms (e.g. changing the domain or adding in another field) an=
d be confident about the risks?

Cheers,
Mike




